column1: #Text=John Korsrud is a Canadian composer and jazz trumpeter .
#Text=Korsrud ( b. 1963 ) , who lives in Vancouver , British Columbia , Canada
#Text=is a composer and leads the 18-piece Hard Rubber Orchestra .
#Text=Korsrud studied composition with Louis Andriessen at the Royal Conservatory in Amsterdam .

#Text=Korsrud has received commissions from the Vancouver Symphony Orchestra , the American Composers Orchestra , The CBC Radio Orchestra , and Dutch ensembles such as Ensemble LOOS , the Tetzepi Bigtet , the Zapp String Quartet , De Ereprijs , among others .
#Text=Korsrud performed on his own trumpet concerto , Come to the Dark Side at Carnegie Hall in 2010 with by The American Composers Orchestra .

#Text=Since 1990 , he has led the 18-piece new music/ jazz ensemble Hard Rubber Orchestra , with which has appeared in Europe and across Canada , recorded three albums , and in 2005 won the Alcan Arts Award .
#Text=The Hard Rubber Orchestra has commissioned over 50 works from composers such as Kenny Wheeler , Darcy James Argue , Brad Turner , Scott Good , Linda Bouchard , Rene Lussier and many others .
#Text=Korsrud also leads the 20-piece Salsa/Latin-Jazz-Orchestra Orquestra Goma Dura , from which an album has appeared , and the 14-piece drum'n'bass ensemble The Drum & Light Orchestra .

#Text=Korsrud has also created large multimedia projects like The Elvis Cantatas ( 1994 , 1996 ) , The Ice Age : The World 's First New Music Ice Show ( 2000 , 2010 ) , and Enter/Exit ( 2005 ) , and The Drum & Light Festival ( 2008 – 10 ) .
#Text=The CBC produced a 70-minute version of Elvis Cantata , entitled Cantata for the King .
#Text=He won the Leo Award and the Golden Sheaf Award for the music to the film Heroines ( 2002 ) , and was nominated for the Gemini Award .
#Text=He won another Leo Award for the film music to Prisoners of Age .

#Text=Korsrud is the recipient of the Canada Council 's " Victor Martyn Lynch-Staunton Award " ( 2015 ) , the City of Vancouver Mayor 's Award for Music ( 2012 ) , The Canada Council 's Joseph S. Stauffer Prize ( 2001 ) , and a fellowship from the Italian Civitella Ranieri Foundation ( 2003 ) .
